properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Lake effect snow squalls will weaken this morning. Lake effect snow bands are currently coming onshore between Point Clark and Southampton. Periods of low visibility in snow are expected with additional snowfall amounts up to 5 cm possible by later this morning. Icy roads have been reported in some areas. Snow squalls will taper to scattered flurries through this morning. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. Snow continues across northern Manitoba today. The snow has been falling quite heavy this morning in a few localities and will continue through the afternoon. With the heavy snow, it is expected to accumulate rapidly. Snow will begin to taper off late in the afternoon and through the evening. Regions in central Manitoba may see some freezing drizzle after the snow departs. The freezing drizzle risk will diminish in the evening and through the overnight. Please refer to local forecasts for additional details on timing and snowfall amounts. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.
